School and Library Subscribers JOIN LOGIN Activate Your Free Trial! stories quizzes galleries lists Disjunction Article Web sites Logic Read View History Edit Feedback Disjunction, in logic, relation or connection of terms in a proposition to express the concept “or”; it is a statement of alternatives (sometimes called “alternation”). For clarity, exclusive disjunction (either x or y, but not both), symbolized x ⊻ y, must be distinguished from inclusive disjunction (either x or y, or both x and y), symbolized x ∨ y. See also implication. Comments Share SHARE Email Print Cite You may also be interested in... connective conjunction implication philosophy logic arthapatti list of philosophers propositional function commutative law associative law term distributive law Keep exploring Name that Mark Literary Hodgepodge Southeast Asia: Fact or Fiction? Cruel and Unusual Punishments: 15 Types of Torture International Literary Tour: 10 Places Every Lit Lover Should See What made you want to look up disjunction? To From Subject Comments (Please limit to 900 characters) Cancel BRITANNICA QUIZZES Canines vs. Felines Africa’s Physical Features Cervantes See More Quizzes MORE QUIZZES The Literary World Who Wrote It: Fact or Fiction? Hinduism See More Quizzes About Us About Our Ads Partner Program Contact Us Privacy Policy Terms of Use ©2016 Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc. Citations MLA style: "disjunction". Encyclopædia Britannica. Encyclopædia Britannica Online. Encyclopædia Britannica Inc., 2016. Web. 14 Apr. 2016 <http://www.britannica.com/topic/disjunction-logic>. APA style: disjunction. (2016). In Encyclopædia Britannica. Retrieved from http://www.britannica.com/topic/disjunction-logic Harvard style: disjunction. 2016. Encyclopædia Britannica Online. Retrieved 14 April, 2016, from http://www.britannica.com/topic/disjunction-logic Chicago Manual of Style: Encyclopædia Britannica Online, s. v. "disjunction", accessed April 14, 2016, http://www.britannica.com/topic/disjunction-l